@Mark Smith
I’m not a civil engineer but I did grow up in Detroit, so I’ve seen these Michigan Lefts in action.  They only occur on divided boulevards. I think the advantage is that traffic does not stop at the light to turn left. (Green arrows for left turns stop nearly all traffic in all directions while the lefts proceed.) Instead, one proceeds through the intersection to the U turn lane, which usually results in the oncoming traffic flow diminishing by the time one gets there, allowing the completion of the u turn and movement into the right lane to prepare for the right turn. Additionally, the subsequent right turn in Michigan can be completed on the red light, affording even more efficiency.
The other method of accomplishing the same left turn is to turn right at the intersection, cross the lanes of traffic to an identical u turn lane, where after accomplishing the u turn one is headed in the desired direction. I found these to be less desirable, as it always seemed by the time one returns to the intersection headed in the right direction the light was already red for proceeding traffic.

@Andrzej
This article has diagrams of the michigan left, the bowtie, and the jug handle. might make things clearer.

"The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) estimates that left turns are a critical event in more than 22% of all traffic accidents, resulting in over 480,000 crashes each year in the United States. In contrast, right-hand turns account for just 1.2% of crashes."  So yes, there's good reason to look for solutions that reduce risk while not bringing the rest of the traffic flow to a grinding halt.

